defs.docs:
The `inlinable_string` crate provides the
 [`InlinableString`](./enum.InlinableString.html) type — an owned,
 grow-able UTF-8 string that stores small strings inline and avoids
 heap-allocation — and the
 [`StringExt`](./string_ext/trait.StringExt.html) trait which abstracts
 string operations over both `std::string::String` and `InlinableString` (or
 even your own custom string type).

attributes.value: / grow-able UTF-8 string that stores small strings inline and avoids

/ deprecated methods are not included. A `StringExt` implementation is
/ provided for both `std::string::String` and `InlinableString`. This enables
/ `InlinableString` to generally work as a drop-in replacement for
/ `std::string::String` and `&StringExt` to work with references to either
/ // Small strings are stored inline and don't perform heap-allocation.
/ // Inline strings are transparently promoted to heap-allocated strings when
/ s.push_str("a really long string that's bigger than `INLINE_STRING_CAPACITY`");
/ // This method can work on strings potentially stored inline on the stack,
/ // on the heap, or plain old `std::string::String`s!
/ let mut s1 = String::from("this is a plain std::string::String");
/ * If `my_string` is always on the stack: `let my_string = String::new();` →
/ * `fn foo(string: &str) { ... }` does not need to be modified.
/ * `struct S { member: String }` is a little trickier. If `S` is always stack
/ allocated, it probably makes sense to make `member` be of type
/ `InlinableString`. If `S` is heap-allocated and `member` is *always* small,
/ not always small, then it should probably be left as a `String`.
/ Add the `serde` feature to your `Cargo.toml` to enable serialization.

defs.name: inline_string
defs.docs:
A short UTF-8 string that uses inline storage and does no heap
 allocation. It may be no longer than `INLINE_STRING_CAPACITY` bytes long.

attributes.value: / A short UTF-8 string that uses inline storage and does no heap
/ allocation. It may be no longer than `INLINE_STRING_CAPACITY` bytes long.
/ The capacity restriction makes many operations that would otherwise be
/ infallible on `std::string::String` fallible. Additionally, many trait
/ interfaces don't allow returning an error when a string runs out of space,
/ and so the trait implementation simply panics. As such, `InlineString` does
/ not implement `StringExt` and is ***not*** a drop-in replacement for
/ aims to be, and is generally difficult to work with. It is not recommended
/ to use this type directly unless you really, really want to avoid heap
/ allocation, can live with the imposed size restrictions, and are willing
/ work around potential sources of panics (eg, in the `From` trait
/ assert!(s.push_str("a really long string that is much bigger than `INLINE_STRING_CAPACITY`").is_err());

defs.name: INLINE_STRING_CAPACITY
defs.docs:
The capacity (in bytes) of inline storage for small strings.
 `InlineString::len()` may never be larger than this.

attributes.value: / The capacity (in bytes) of inline storage for small strings.
/ `InlineString::len()` may never be larger than this.
/ Sometime in the future, when Rust's generics support specializing with
/ compile-time static integers, this number should become configurable.
